members.name: None
members.description: If there's no way we can detect to insert new plugs.

members.name: InventorySourced
members.description:
Use plugs found in the player's inventory, based on the socket type rules (see DestinySocketTypeDefinition for more info)
Note that a socket - like Shaders - can have *both* reusable plugs and inventory items inserted theoretically.

members.name: ReusablePlugItems
members.description:
Use the DestinyItemSocketsComponent.sockets.reusablePlugs property to determine which plugs are valid for this socket. This may have to be combined with other sources, such as plug sets, if those flags are set.
 Note that "Reusable" plugs may not necessarily come from a plug set, nor from the "reusablePlugItems" in the socket's Definition data. They can sometimes be "randomized" in which case the only source of truth at the moment is still the runtime DestinyItemSocketsComponent.sockets.reusablePlugs property.

members.name: ProfilePlugSet
members.description: Use the ProfilePlugSets (DestinyProfileResponse.profilePlugSets) component data to determine which plugs are valid for this socket.

members.name: CharacterPlugSet
members.description: Use the CharacterPlugSets (DestinyProfileResponse.characterPlugSets) component data to determine which plugs are valid for this socket.

members.name: Crucible
members.description: DEPRECATED. Items can be both "Crucible" and something else interesting.

members.name: Vanguard
members.description: DEPRECATED. An item can both be "Vanguard" and something else.

members.name: Exotic
members.description: DEPRECATED. An item can both be Exotic and something else.

members.name: Crm
members.description: DEPRECATED. An item can both be CRM and something else.

members.name: Default
members.description: The original rank progression from token redemption.

members.name: Ritual
members.description: Progression from ranks in ritual content. For example: Crucible (Shaxx), Gambit (Drifter), and Season 13 Battlegrounds (War Table).

members.name: NoSeasonalRefresh
members.description: A vendor progression with no seasonal refresh. For example: Xur in the Eternity destination for the 30th Anniversary.

members.name: Undefined
members.description: An empty interaction. If this ends up in content, it is probably a game bug.

members.name: QuestComplete
members.description: An interaction shown when you complete a quest and receive a reward.

members.name: QuestContinue
members.description: An interaction shown when you talk to a Vendor as an intermediary step of a quest.

members.name: ReputationPreview
members.description: An interaction shown when you are previewing the vendor's reputation rewards.

members.name: RankUpReward
members.description: An interaction shown when you rank up with the vendor.

members.name: TokenTurnIn
members.description: An interaction shown when you have tokens to turn in for the vendor.

members.name: QuestAccept
members.description: An interaction shown when you're accepting a new quest.

members.name: ProgressTab
members.description: Honestly, this doesn't seem consistent to me. It is used to give you choices in the Cryptarch as well as some reward prompts by the Eververse vendor. I'll have to look into that further at some point.

members.name: End
members.description: These seem even less consistent. I don't know what these are.

members.name: Start
members.description: Also seem inconsistent. I also don't know what these are offhand.

members.name: Clash
members.description: Clash -> Destiny's name for Team Deathmatch. 4v4 combat, the team with the highest kills at the end of time wins.

members.name: Automatic
members.description: Generally, Automatic means "Just show the number"

members.name: Fraction
members.description: Show the number as a fractional value. For this to make sense, the value being displayed should have a comparable upper bound, like the progress to the next level of a Progression.

members.name: Checkbox
members.description: Show the number as a checkbox. 0 Will mean unchecked, any other value will mean checked.

members.name: Percentage
members.description: Show the number as a percentage. For this to make sense, the value being displayed should have a comparable upper bound, like the progress to the next level of a Progression.

members.name: DateTime
members.description: Show the number as a date and time. The number will be the number of seconds since the Unix Epoch (January 1st, 1970 at midnight UTC). It'll be up to you to convert this into a date and time format understandable to the user in their time zone.

members.name: FractionFloat
members.description: Show the number as a floating point value that represents a fraction, where 0 is min and 1 is max. For this to make sense, the value being displayed should have a comparable upper bound, like the progress to the next level of a Progression.

members.name: Integer
members.description: Show the number as a straight-up integer.

members.name: TimeDuration
members.description: Show the number as a time duration. The value will be returned as seconds.

members.name: Hidden
members.description: Don't bother showing the value at all, it's not easily human-interpretable, and used for some internal purpose.

members.name: Multiplier
members.description: Example: "1.5x"

members.name: GreenPips
members.description: Show the value as a series of green pips, like the wins in a Trials of Osiris score card.

members.name: RedPips
members.description: Show the value as a series of red pips, like the losses in a Trials of Osiris score card.

members.name: ExplicitPercentage
members.description: Show the value as a percentage. For example: "51%" - Does no division, only appends '%'

members.name: RawFloat
members.description: Show the value as a floating-point number. For example: "4.52" NOTE: Passed along from Investment as whole number with last two digits as decimal values (452 -> 4.52)

members.name: LevelAndReward
members.description: Show the value as a level and a reward.

members.name: None
members.description: Activities that are neither PVP nor PVE, such as social activities.

members.name: PvE
members.description: PvE activities, where you shoot aliens in the face.

members.name: PvP
members.description: PvP activities, where you shoot your "friends".

members.name: PvECompetitive
members.description: PVE competitive activities, where you shoot whoever you want whenever you want. Or run around collecting small glowing triangles.

members.name: None
members.description: The source doesn't fit well into any of the other types.

members.name: Activity
members.description: The source is directly related to the rewards gained by playing an activity or set of activities. This currently includes Quests and other action in-game.

members.name: Vendor
members.description: This source is directly related to items that Vendors sell.

members.name: Aggregate
members.description: This source is a custom aggregation of items that can be earned in many ways, but that share some other property in common that is useful to share. For instance, in Destiny 1 we would make "Reward Sources" for every game expansion: that way, you could search reward sources to see what items became available with any given Expansion.

members.name: Category
members.description: Display the item as a category, through which sub-items are filtered.

members.name: Default
members.description: Use the "default" view for the presentation nodes.

members.name: CategorySets
members.description: Show sub-items as "category sets". In-game, you'd see these as a vertical list of child presentation nodes - armor sets for example - and the icons of items within those sets displayed horizontally.

members.name: Badge
members.description: Show sub-items as Badges. (I know, I know. We don't need no stinkin' badges har har har)

members.name: MilestoneDefinition
members.description: Indicates you should show DestinyMilestoneDefinition.displayProperties for this Milestone.

members.name: CurrentQuestSteps
members.description: Indicates you should show the displayProperties for any currently active Quest Steps in DestinyMilestone.availableQuests.

members.name: CurrentActivityChallenges
members.description: Indicates you should show the displayProperties for any currently active Activities and their Challenges in DestinyMilestone.activities.

members.name: Tutorial
members.description: One-time milestones that are specifically oriented toward teaching players about new mechanics and gameplay modes.

members.name: OneTime
members.description: Milestones that, once completed a single time, can never be repeated.

members.name: Weekly
members.description: Milestones that repeat/reset on a weekly basis. They need not all reset on the same day or time, but do need to reset weekly to qualify for this type.

members.name: Daily
members.description: Milestones that repeat or reset on a daily basis.

members.name: Special
members.description: Special indicates that the event is not on a daily/weekly cadence, but does occur more than once. For instance, Iron Banner in Destiny 1 or the Dawning were examples of what could be termed "Special" events.
